If you forgot the derivative of $\arccos(x)$, you can use trig
substitutions to derive it. The first step though remains the same: Let
$u = x^{2}$ so that $du = 2xdx$. Then

\begin{align*}
\int\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^{4}}}\, dx  = \frac{1}{2}\int\frac{du}{\sqrt{1-u^{2}}}
\end{align*}

Now, let $u = \sin\theta$ so $du = \cos\theta d\theta$. Then

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}\int\frac{du}{\sqrt{1-u^{2}}} = \frac{1}{2} \int \frac{\cos\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{1 - \sin^{2}\theta}}
\end{align*}

Using the trig identity $\sin^{2}\theta + \cos^{2}\theta =1$, we have

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} \int \frac{\cos\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{1 - \sin^{2}\theta}} &= \frac{1}{2}\int\frac{\cos\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{\cos^{2}\theta}} \\
&= \frac{1}{2}\int d\theta \\
&= \frac{\theta}{2} + C\\
&= \frac{\arcsin(u)}{2} + C \\
&= \frac{\arcsin(x^{2})}{2} + C
\end{align*}

completing the question.

\emph{Notice that this answer is different from the answer in the
previous part. However, since}

\begin{align*}
\arccos(x) + \arcsin(x) = \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*}

\emph{the answers are actually the same up to a constant!}
